I&#39;ve made an app with similiar circumstances, many states, too much hassle. So what you suggested in the second approach is better. It&#39;s always good to have global components and render according to the state you want. 
Suppose you have 2 states and want to display 2 different components. 

1. Create two files X.js and Y.js which you want to render on state1 and state2 respectively.

2.Make a Home.js class where you keep track of state , and import the above two components in it and render according to the condition :

    import X from &#39;X.js&#39;
    import Y from &#39;Y.js&#39;
    
    class Home extends Component {
    
    constructor(props){
    super(props)
    this.state={
    state1:false,
    state2:true
    }
    }
    
    
    render(){
    
    return(
    &lt;View&gt;
    {this.state.state1?&lt;X /&gt;:&lt;View /&gt;}
    {this.state.state2?&lt;Y /&gt;:&lt;View /&gt;}
    &lt;/View&gt;
    
    )
    }
    
    }


Not only does this increase your readability of the code but you actually follow the fractal folder structure of breaking down each component.

