Use `not exists`:

    SELECT s.name
    FROM Store s
    WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1
                      FROM StockInfo si
                      WHERE si.id = s.id AND
                            si.productRelease &gt;= &#39;2003-01-01&#39;
                     );

Presumably `id` is the code for the *store*.  This should be called something more descriptive, like `storeId`, if you have control over the data model.  Similarly, `name` should not be repeated in both `store` and `stockInfo`.

In addition, `SELECT DISTINCT` should not be necessary for this query or for your version.

Since `StockInfo` contains the column `name` of the stores there is no need to use the table `Store`.&lt;br/&gt;
With `NOT EXISTS`:

    SELECT DISTINCT s.name FROM StockInfo s
    WHERE NOT EXISTS (
      SELECT 1 FROM StockInfo
      WHERE name = s.name AND productRelease &gt; &#39;2003-01-01&#39;
    )
Or:

    SELECT name 
    FROM StockInfo
    GROUP BY name
    HAVING MAX(productRelease) &lt;= &#39;2003-01-01&#39;

